1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,602
First we fix our formal language L. It was Frege in

2
00:00:02,702 --> 00:00:05,993
the 1800's who realized that the act of doing mathematics simply

3
00:00:06,093 --> 00:00:09,173
involves the manipulations of the following sets of symbols:

4
00:00:09,266 --> 00:00:13,137
Constant symbols, which represent special elements of a given structure like

5
00:00:13,237 --> 00:00:15,070
0, 1, e, pi or the root of some tree.

6
00:00:15,133 --> 00:00:20,519
Function symbols, such as successor, addition, multiplication.

7
00:00:20,600 --> 00:00:24,078
Relation symbols, such as less than or in.

8
00:00:24,200 --> 00:00:27,522
Variables, quantifiers, and brackets.

9
00:00:27,600 --> 00:00:29,302
The boolean connectives,

10
00:00:29,400 --> 00:00:30,788
of negation,

11
00:00:30,866 --> 00:00:32,203
conjunctions,

12
00:00:32,333 --> 00:00:33,826
disjunction

13
00:00:33,933 --> 00:00:35,923
and implication.

14
00:00:36,533 --> 00:00:38,642
The Boolean connectives can be represented

15
00:00:38,742 --> 00:00:40,273
by truth tables or logic gates.

16
00:00:40,333 --> 00:00:46,215
Note that in classical logic, a implies b is equivalent to not a or b.

17
00:00:46,266 --> 00:00:49,061
This is not the case in intuitionistic logic for example.

18
00:00:49,161 --> 00:00:51,703
But for this video we will stick to classical logic,

19
00:00:51,803 --> 00:00:54,344
and soon I will make a video on non-classical logics

20
00:00:54,444 --> 00:00:57,138
and they give rise to different mathematical universes.

21
00:00:57,200 --> 00:01:00,127
We can divide these symbols into two groups, the logical

22
00:01:00,227 --> 00:01:03,478
and non-logical symbols. The logical symbols are common to all

23
00:01:03,578 --> 00:01:06,830
first order theories, and so proofs only involving the logical

24
00:01:06,930 --> 00:01:10,993
symbols apply to all possible first-order structures. The non-logical symbols

25
00:01:11,093 --> 00:01:12,668
are specific to a given theory,

26
00:01:12,733 --> 00:01:15,948
for example if we are working with the theory of arithmetic, we

27
00:01:16,048 --> 00:01:19,947
only need the constant 0, the successor function, and the addition function.

28
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:22,524
Whereas, if we work with the theory of graphs, we

29
00:01:22,624 --> 00:01:25,362
only need a single binary relation E, where aEb means

30
00:01:25,462 --> 00:01:27,397
that there is an edge between a and b.

